## <center>Introduction</center>

#### TNT's 3 Stages

* **Target Prediction:** propose a set of plausible targets among all candidates;
* **Target-Conditioned Motion Estimation:** estimates a trajectory (distribution) towards each selected target;
* **Trajectory Scoring and Selection:** ranks trajectory hypotheses and selects a final set of trajectory predictions with likelihood scores.

## <center>Related Work</center>

#### capture the underlying intents of the agents

*  DESIRE used a conditional VAE
*  PRECOG used flow-based generative models
* SocialGAN proposed an adversarial discriminator to predict realistic futures
* Honget modeled the motion patterns with a latent Gaussian mixture model

#### decompose the trajectory prediction task into subtasks

* Ziebartet proposed planning-based prediction for pedestrians
  * first estimate a Bayesian posterior distribution of destinations
  * then use inverse reinforcementlearning (IRL) to plan the trajectories
* Rehderet introduced the notion of goals which aredefined as short-term destinations, and decomposed the problem into goal distribution estimationand goal-directed planning
* Mangalam proposed to generate endpoints to guide the full trajectory generation

#### discretize the output space

* IntentNet
  * manually defined several common motion categories for self-driving vehicles
  * learned a separate motion predictor for each intent
  * is task and dataset dependent, and may be too coarse to capture intra-category multimodality
* MultiPath, CoverNet
  * quantize the trajectories into anchors
  * the trajectory prediction task is reformulated into anchor selection and offset regression

## <center>Formulation</center>

* Observed State: $$ S_{P} = [ S_{-T'+1}, S_{-T'+2}, ..., S_{0} ]$$
* Future State: $$ S_{F} = [S_{1}, S_{2}, ..., S_{T} ] $$
* Environment: $$ C_{P} = [ C_{-T'+1}, C_{-T'+2}, ..., C_{0} ]$$
* denote $$ X = (S_{P}, C_{P}) $$
* Probabilistic distribution to capture:

$$p( S_{F}|X)$$

## <center>Target-driveN Trajectory Prediction</center>

#### Scene context encoding

* use <hu>VectorNet</hu> to encode the context
  * polylines are used to abstract the HD map elements(lanes, traffic signs) and agent trajectories
  * a subgraph network is applied to encode each polyline, which contains a variable number of vectors
  * a global graph is used to model the interactions between polylines
